lied to the document after `b` was applied\n- `b'` should be applied to the document after `a` was applied\n\nSo `a'` = `[1, \"C\"]` should be applied to the document that results from applying `b` = `[1, \"B\"]` to the base. The base here is \"A\" (after ops[0]). Apply `[1, \"B\"]` to \"A\" gives \"AB\". So we need to apply `[1, \"C\"]` to \"AB\" - but `[1, \"C\"]` has inputLength 1, and \"AB\" has length 2. That's the bug.\n\nThe fix: `a'` should retain the full length. Looking at the transform output: `[1, \"C\"]` has retain 1 + insert \"C\". But the document after ops[1] is 2 chars. So the transform is wrong.\n\nLet me re-examine my transform function. Actually wait, let me re-trace more carefully.\n\ntransform(`[1, \"C\"]`, `[1, \"B\"]`):\n\n```\nStep 1: typeA=retain, typeB=retain\n  lenA = 1, lenB = 1, minLen = 1\n  iterA.take(1) -> 1 (consumes retain 1)\n  iterB.take(1) -> 1 (consumes retain 1)\n  aPrime = [1], bPrime = [1]\n\nStep 2: typeA=insert(\"C\"), priority=left, typeB=insert(\"B\")\n  -> typeA is insert AND priority is left, so a's insert goes first\n  ins = iterA.takeInsert() -> \"C\"\n  aPrime = [1, \"C\"], bPrime = [1, 1]\n\nStep 3: typeB=insert(\"B\")\n  ins = iterB.takeInsert() -> \"B\"\n  bPrime = [1, 1, \"B\"] = [2, \"B\"], aPrime = [1, \"C\", 1]\n\nDone.\n```\n\nAh, I missed step 3! After inserting \"C\" from A, we loop back and typeB is now insert(\"B\"). So:\n- aPrime = `[1, \"C\", 1]` → inputLength = 1 + 1 = 2. output = \"?\" + \"C\" + \"?\". \n\nWait, `[1, \"C\", 1]` has inputLength = 2 (retain 1 + retain 1). outputLength = 1 + 1 + 1 = 3. So `a'` expects a 2-char document and produces 3 chars. Applied to \"AB\" → \"A\" + \"C\" + \"B\" = \"ACB\". That makes sense!\n\nSo my initial trace was wrong - I missed the continuation of the loop. Let me re-check: is the actual test failing due to a code bug, or just a timing issue?\n\nThe test timeout suggests a timing issue, not a logic bug. Let me check if the 10-client test just needs more time. T